<div id="review_2350504376" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2350504376" />
    <a title="Ron" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9857155-ron"><img alt="Ron" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1338295371p2/9857155.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2350504376?book_show_action=true">Apr 04, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ron" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ron" href="/user/show/9857155-ron">Ron</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2350504376" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3107152006825929025">In three different periods of history, European civilization is deteriorating, and the three main characters find themselves having to decide what to do about it. It is about surviving imminent catastrophe, about the difficulty of knowing how to act well when the odds against survival are diminishing. Manlius, suave, sophisticated, versed in the depths of Neoplatonic philosophy, sees that late Roman civilization in Gaul is falling apart, and, with the Goths and the Burgundians, barbarian tribes </span>
  <span id="freeText3107152006825929025" style="display:none">In three different periods of history, European civilization is deteriorating, and the three main characters find themselves having to decide what to do about it. It is about surviving imminent catastrophe, about the difficulty of knowing how to act well when the odds against survival are diminishing. Manlius, suave, sophisticated, versed in the depths of Neoplatonic philosophy, sees that late Roman civilization in Gaul is falling apart, and, with the Goths and the Burgundians, barbarian tribes from the north, encroaching, the only possible source of stability and cultural control is in the church. A skeptic about Christianity, he nevertheless manages to convert, and be named bishop of Provence, in which role he turns against his oldest friend, allows the Burgundians to take ostensible control while he struggles to maintain what he can of the culture and stability he has known as a Roman citizen. In the 1300s, Olivier de Noyen discovers Manlius's manuscripts, and finds himself first working with Cardinal Ceccani to preserve other lost ancient documents, then having to use his influence with the church, little as it is, to save Jews that Cecanni wants to use as scapegoats for the plague. In 1940s Europe, classical scholar Julien Barneuve discovers Olivier's copies of Manlius and strives to piece together the two stories as he finds himself embroiled in the moral compromises of Vichy occupation. <br />A wonderful book, complex, but readable, full of really deep and fascinating characters. As soon as I finished, I started it again, to get clearer in my head how the three stories started to intertwine after I had seen how they all turn out (none of them happily, though perhaps each of the main characters ends up as well as might be expected, given their situations.) A thoughtful dramatization of how individuals find themselves caught up in history, and how they work through their roles to find some kind of meaningful action, which, Sophia contends, is the only path to virtue possible.<br />I will remember the vividly evoked context of each story, especially the Manlius story, which conveys what it meant to an ordinary person when the authority of Rome collapsed. I will remember the bittersweet ironies of both Sophia and Manlius, the epitome of high pagan philosophical sophistication, being accepted as saints of the Christian church, which neither believed in. I will remember the way Pisano the painter was inspired by the local legends of Sts. Sophia and Manlius to paint the frescoes in the chapel that had been Sophia's refuge, and then how Julia, taking refuge herself in the chapel as the Germans, the new barbarians, move slowly south, is inspired by the frescoes to perfect her own art in the 20th century.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3107152006825929025" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

