<div id="review_2523183453" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2523183453" />
    <a title="martin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16675-martin"><img alt="martin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1185961568p2/16675.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2523183453?book_show_action=true">Sep 08, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="martin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="martin" href="/user/show/16675-martin">martin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2523183453" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5719380397230882229">An extremely ambitious novel that focuses on weighty questions like the purpose, role and value of culture and civilisation in times when the &quot;recognised&quot; order is collapsing; bringing in anti-semitism; xenophobia; the role of Christianity, personal belief, rationality, friendship, loyalty, honesty. Its conclusions on these are fairly damning in many ways. <br/><br/>The danger with something of this enormous scope is that it becomes too worthy and takes itself too seriously. I felt that something like tha</span>
  <span id="freeText5719380397230882229" style="display:none">An extremely ambitious novel that focuses on weighty questions like the purpose, role and value of culture and civilisation in times when the "recognised" order is collapsing; bringing in anti-semitism; xenophobia; the role of Christianity, personal belief, rationality, friendship, loyalty, honesty. Its conclusions on these are fairly damning in many ways. <br /><br />The danger with something of this enormous scope is that it becomes too worthy and takes itself too seriously. I felt that something like that happened here. I'm a huge fan of An Instance of the Fingerpost, so the fairly complex structure moving rapidly between 3 interlinked and parallel plots spread over 1500 years came as no surprise, but unfortunately I found it confusing. The common thread provided by Graeco-Roman philosophy and learning is important but I found myself wanting to stick with one story out of the three instead of endlessly flitting back and forth across the centuries. The complex plot also requires a very lengthy exposition. I'd read a third of the book and still felt I was in the introduction. <br /><br />Strengths? Yes, the writing is thought provoking and clever, the plot construction is well thought through. The main characters are multi-dimensional and fascinating. The research done must have been intensive and lengthy and that makes it a significant achievement too. Oddly though, having recently read 2 other novels set in wartime France, I was surprised at how easily Julien gets out of Paris and travel south just as France is falling. <br /><br />Overall, it's a juggernaut of a book, very slow to get up to speed but once there it's definitely a provocative read</span>
  <a data-text-id="5719380397230882229" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

