<div id="review_2353933789" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2353933789" />
    <a title="Betsy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8355999-betsy"><img alt="Betsy" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2353933789?book_show_action=true">Apr 07, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Betsy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Betsy" href="/user/show/8355999-betsy">Betsy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8355999-betsy?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8355999-betsy?shelf=2018">2018</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2353933789" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9555291642389529183">it is hard to know what to say about this book. I have read several of his other books, a light mystery series about an art historian and his girlfriend/wife, an investigator for the (fictitious) Italian Art Squad. The Dream of Scipio is nothing like those books. It is three stories about the choices people make in times of crisis, specifically what their responsibilities are to individuals vs. to &quot;civilization&quot; in general and, in fact, what constitutes the idea of civilization. The stories are </span>
  <span id="freeText9555291642389529183" style="display:none">it is hard to know what to say about this book. I have read several of his other books, a light mystery series about an art historian and his girlfriend/wife, an investigator for the (fictitious) Italian Art Squad. The Dream of Scipio is nothing like those books. It is three stories about the choices people make in times of crisis, specifically what their responsibilities are to individuals vs. to "civilization" in general and, in fact, what constitutes the idea of civilization. The stories are connected by a document (the dream) that examines these issues. Conflicts between religions (early Christianity vs. neo-Platonism, later Christian persecution of Jews during the middle ages and WWII) for a common theme. This is a pretty dark book, but very interesting.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9555291642389529183" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


